            <entry xml:id="entry_ædemonæj" xml:lang="os-x-digor">
                <form xml:id="form_d181e66" type="lemma"><orth>ædemonæj</orth><form xml:id="form_d181e68" type="variant"><orth>ædemontæj</orth></form></form>
                <usg><lang/></usg>
                <sense xml:id="sense_d181e74"><sense xml:id="sense_d181e75"><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>безотчетно</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>instinctively</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense><sense xml:id="sense_d181e84"><abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>необдуманно</q>
                        </abv:tr><abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>thoughtlessly</q>
                        </abv:tr></sense></sense>
                <abv:exampleGrp xml:id="exampleGrp_d181e94">
                    <abv:example xml:id="example_d181e96">
                        <quote>fal æ zærdæ otæ ʽnconæj kæd sijjevuj silæstæg, o, me ʽngaræ, ædemonæj
                            warzt ma xonæ wæd suǧdæg</quote>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="ru">
                            <q>но если женщина так легко меняет сердце, о, мой друг, не считай тогда
                                необдуманно (такую) любовь чистой“</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <abv:tr xml:lang="en">
                            <q>but if a woman changes her heart so easily, oh, my friend, then do
                                not recklessly consider (such) love pure "</q>
                        </abv:tr>
                        <bibl><ref type="bibl" target="#src_Iræf"/><biblScope>6</biblScope></bibl>
                    </abv:example>
                </abv:exampleGrp>
                <etym xml:lang="ru">Восходит к <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*a-daiman-</hi>, буквально „не посмотрев (как
                    следует)“, ‘не разобравшись’; см. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_æ-"/> (←
                        <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e205" xml:id="mentioned_d181e120" xml:lang="x-oldirn"><lang/>
                        <w>a-</w></mentioned>) привативная частица и <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e210" xml:id="mentioned_d181e125" xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>daeman-</w>
                        <gloss><q>глаз</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e218" xml:id="mentioned_d181e133" xml:lang="ae"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>взгляд</q></gloss></mentioned> (от <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e224" xml:id="mentioned_d181e139" xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>day-</w>
                        <gloss><q>смотреть</q></gloss></mentioned>). Ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_fældemæn"/> (← <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*pari-daiman</hi> ‘лживый’, ‘обманный’ и <ref type="xr" target="#entry_wældemonæj"/> (← <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*upari-daiman</hi> ‘намеками’,
                    ‘иносказательно’. В основах на <hi rendition="#rend_italic">-аn</hi> формант <hi rendition="#rend_italic">-an</hi> в осетинском обычно не
                    удерживается (ср. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_casm"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_nom"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_wyrs"/> и др.). В
                    данном случае, учитывая наречное употребление слова, можно думать, что исходной
                    была форма не именительного, а косвенного падежа (instr. <hi rendition="#rend_italic">daimana-</hi>?).
                    Древнеиранское <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e243" xml:id="mentioned_d181e158" xml:lang="x-oldirn"><lang/>
                        <w>*daiman-</w></mentioned> прослеживается и в других иранских языках:
                        <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e249" xml:id="mentioned_d181e164" xml:lang="xpr"><lang/>
                        <w>andēman</w>
                        <gloss><q>открыто</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e257" xml:id="mentioned_d181e172" xml:lang="sog"><lang/>
                        <w>δym</w></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e262" xml:id="mentioned_d181e177" xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>dīm</w>
                        <gloss><q>выражение лица</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e270" xml:id="mentioned_d181e185" xml:lang="ps"><lang/>
                        <w>lemə</w>
                        <gloss><q>глазное
                            яблоко</q></gloss></mentioned>.%n<bibl><author>Gershevitch</author><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_BSOAS"/><biblScope xml:lang="ru">XIV (1952), ч.
                            3, стр. 485</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
                <etym xml:lang="en">Traces back to <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*a-daiman-</hi>, literally “without looking
                    (properly)”, “without understanding”; cf.<ref type="xr" target="#entry_æ-"/> (←
                        <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e120" xml:id="mentioned_d181e205" xml:lang="x-oldirn"><lang/>
                        <w>a-</w></mentioned>), privative particle, and <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e125" xml:id="mentioned_d181e210" xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>daeman-</w>
                        <gloss><q>eye</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e133" xml:id="mentioned_d181e218" xml:lang="ae"><w/>
                        <gloss><q>look</q></gloss></mentioned> (from <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e139" xml:id="mentioned_d181e224" xml:lang="ae"><lang/>
                        <w>day-</w>
                        <gloss><q>look (v.)</q></gloss></mentioned>). Cf. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_fældemæn"/> (← <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*pari-daiman</hi> ‘deceitful’, ‘deceiving’,
                        and<ref type="xr" target="#entry_wældemonæj"/> (← <hi rendition="#rend_italic">*upari-daiman</hi> ‘by
                    hints’, ‘allegorically’. In stems ending in <hi rendition="#rend_italic">-an</hi> the formant <hi rendition="#rend_italic">-an</hi> is
                    usually not preserved in Ossetic (cf. <ref type="xr" target="#entry_casm"/>,
                        <ref type="xr" target="#entry_nom"/>, <ref type="xr" target="#entry_wyrs"/>
                    etc.). In this case, given the adverbial use of the word, one may think that the
                    original was not the nominative, but the oblique case form (instr.
                    <hi rendition="#rend_italic">daimana-</hi>?). The ancient Iranian <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e158" xml:id="mentioned_d181e243" xml:lang="x-oldirn"><lang/>
                        <w>*daiman-</w></mentioned> can be traced in other Iranian languages:
                        <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e164" xml:id="mentioned_d181e249" xml:lang="xpr"><lang/>
                        <w>andēman</w>
                        <gloss><q>overtly</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e172" xml:id="mentioned_d181e257" xml:lang="sog"><lang/>
                        <w>δym</w></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e177" xml:id="mentioned_d181e262" xml:lang="fa"><lang/>
                        <w>dīm</w>
                        <gloss><q>facial expression</q></gloss></mentioned>, <mentioned corresp="#mentioned_d181e185" xml:id="mentioned_d181e270" xml:lang="ps"><lang/>
                        <w>lemə</w>
                        <gloss><q>eyeball</q></gloss></mentioned>.%n<bibl><author>Gershevitch</author><ref type="bibl" target="#ref_BSOAS"/><biblScope xml:lang="en"> XIV (1952), pt. 3, p.
                            485</biblScope></bibl>.</etym>
            </entry>
